Computational Repurposing of FDA-Approved Sigma-1 Receptor Agonists for Neuroprotection via ER-MAM Calcium Regulation: A Molecular Docking Study

Balogun Ajibola Zubur¹*
¹Federal University of Technology, Akure, Nigeria
*Corresponding Author | Email: ajibolazb@gmail.com | Phone: +234 9166372304
Neurodegeneration involves neuronal death via calcium excitotoxicity and mitochondria-associated apoptosis driven by dysregulated ER-MAM calcium signalling. Sigma-1 Receptor (SIGMAR1), an ER-MAM chaperone, regulates IP3R-mediated calcium flux and represents a validated neuroprotective target. This study computationally screened FDA-approved SIGMAR1 agonists as repurposing candidates. A total of 8,440 SIGMAR1-binding compounds from ChEMBL (CHEMBL287) were filtered by agonist mechanism, Phase 4 status, and molecular properties, yielding five candidates: raloxifene, donepezil, dextromethorphan, fluvoxamine, and pentazocine (reference standard). Ligands were converted to PDBQT using Open Babel. The receptor (PDB: 6DK1, Chain A) was prepared by removing the co-crystallized ligand, water molecules, and heteroatoms, with polar hydrogens added at pH 7.4. Molecular docking employed AutoDockVina with a 25×25×25 Å grid centered on the pentazocine binding pocket. Docked complexes underwent protein-ligand interaction profiling (PLIP) and ADMET assessment via SwissADME and ADMETlab 3.0. Raloxifene exhibited the highest binding affinity (−10.630 kcal/mol), followed by donepezil (−10.500 kcal/mol), dextromethorphan (−10.100 kcal/mol), pentazocine (−8.823 kcal/mol), and fluvoxamine (−7.291 kcal/mol). The top three candidates exhibited 14-20% superior binding versus pentazocine. Despite its superior docking score, raloxifene exhibited critical ADMET liabilities: poor BBB penetrance, hERG toxicity risk, and genotoxicity. Donepezil demonstrated favorable ADMET compliance (low P-gp efflux: 0.04, hERG risk: 0.94) and confirmed CNS pharmacokinetics. Donepezil emerges as the optimal repurposing candidate for ER-MAM calcium stabilization, offering immediate translational potential given its established Alzheimer's disease safety profile and superior SIGMAR1 affinity. Future work will pursue lead optimisation of raloxifene through fluorine substitution and methoxy capping to generate 4-fluoro-4-methoxy-raloxifene with improved CNS penetrance.
Keywords: Sigma-1 Receptor; Drug Repurposing; Molecular Docking; Neuroprotection; ER-MAM


Subtheme: Molecular Therapeutics, Drug Discovery and Diagnostic Innovations.

